{"repo": "fairlearn/fairlearn", "pull_number": 1637, "instance_id": "fairlearn__fairlearn-1637", "issue_numbers": [1475], "base_commit": "4b384fe5afc36b7ffdb280621d98118163254a1a", "patch": "diff --git a/docs/user_guide/assessment/advanced_metricframe.rst b/docs/user_guide/assessment/advanced_metricframe.rst\nindex 542de2836..94a05f6e6 100644\n--- a/docs/user_guide/assessment/advanced_metricframe.rst\n+++ b/docs/user_guide/assessment/advanced_metricframe.rst\n@@ -169,6 +169,29 @@ For example:\n     c    0.50\n     Name: selection_rate, dtype: float64\n \n+Another example of a metric that only uses :code:`y_pred` is\n+:func:`mean_prediction`, which computes the average predicted value\n+for each group. This is useful for detecting prediction bias \u2014\n+for instance, whether a model systematically assigns higher risk\n+scores to one group over another.\n+\n+.. doctest:: advanced_metricframe_code\n+    :options:  +NORMALIZE_WHITESPACE\n+\n+    >>> from fairlearn.metrics import mean_prediction\n+    >>> mean_pred_frame = MetricFrame(metrics=mean_prediction,\n+    ...                               y_true=dummy_y_true,\n+    ...                               y_pred=y_pred,\n+    ...                               sensitive_features=pd.Series(sf_data, name='SF 0'))\n+    >>> mean_pred_frame.overall.item()\n+    0.55555...\n+    >>> mean_pred_frame.by_group\n+    SF 0\n+    a    0.75\n+    b    0.50\n+    c    0.50\n+    Name: mean_prediction, dtype: float64\n+\n \n .. _more_complex_metrics:\n \n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "DOC Identify and list components of the API that could benefit from short examples in the documentation\n#### Describe the issue linked to the documentation\r\nThe [Fairlearn API](https://fairlearn.org/v0.12/api_reference/index.html) still has many of it's components not covered by short examples that show their functionality in the [User Guide](https://fairlearn.org/v0.12/user_guide/index.html). \r\n\r\n<!--\r\nTell us about the confusion introduced in the documentation.\r\n-->\r\n\r\n#### Suggest a potential alternative/fix\r\nAdding more examples of example usage of the different components of the API in the User Guide.\r\nSome of the examples can be added within the existing documents, but the User Guide can also be expanded. \r\n\r\n**A big step forward would be go to through the API reference and identify which components aren't already in the User Guide and create a list as part of this issue.** \r\n\r\nWhile not directly merging anything, this issue provides great value for the project. The benefit for the contributor is getting familiar with the API in detail and easily picking up subsequent tasks. \r\n\r\nAn example of such a short example in the user guide of a PR we merged recently: \r\n- [Place in the docs where it resides](https://fairlearn.org/v0.12/user_guide/mitigation/reductions.html#exponentiated-gradient)\r\n- The PR discussion around it: https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/pull/1353\r\n\r\nFeel free to ping me with any questions! You can also go ahead and open a PR about adding an example that is missing.\r\n\r\n<!--\r\nTell us how we could improve the documentation in this regard.\r\n-->\r\n\n", "hints_text": "I am working on adding an example for `ErrorRate`.\nHi @StefanieSenger, are there maybe some functions/classes you came upon searching what to do that you decided not to go into and you could list here? It is ok if not, maybe we can leave a breadcrumb for the next person. Thanks!\nHi @TamaraAtanasoska, this issue is pretty similar to #987 opened by @hildeweerts. Would it make sense to consolidate these two issues?\nyes they definitely can be consolidated into a larger project. both the tasks are still relevant though, as a list with all the missing information make it more tangible for the newcomers to the project.\n> yes they definitely can be consolidated into a larger project. both the tasks are still relevant though, as a list with all the missing information make it more tangible for the newcomers to the project.\n\nUnderstood\nHi, I noticed make_derived_metric doesn't have an example in the User Guide. Ran into this while building a churn model. Adding one with transform='difference' might be useful. Happy to work on this if no one else is on it!\nActually, I looked more carefully and saw it already has an example in custom_fairness_metrics.rst. I'll check the other components and follow up with something that's actually missing\n\n", "all_hints_text": "I am working on adding an example for `ErrorRate`.\nHi @StefanieSenger, are there maybe some functions/classes you came upon searching what to do that you decided not to go into and you could list here? It is ok if not, maybe we can leave a breadcrumb for the next person. Thanks!\nHi @TamaraAtanasoska, this issue is pretty similar to #987 opened by @hildeweerts. Would it make sense to consolidate these two issues?\nyes they definitely can be consolidated into a larger project. both the tasks are still relevant though, as a list with all the missing information make it more tangible for the newcomers to the project.\n> yes they definitely can be consolidated into a larger project. both the tasks are still relevant though, as a list with all the missing information make it more tangible for the newcomers to the project.\n\nUnderstood\nHi, I noticed make_derived_metric doesn't have an example in the User Guide. Ran into this while building a churn model. Adding one with transform='difference' might be useful. Happy to work on this if no one else is on it!\nActually, I looked more carefully and saw it already has an example in custom_fairness_metrics.rst. I'll check the other components and follow up with something that's actually missing\nOpened PR #1637 for mean_prediction\nIt looks like the CI failures are due to plot_credit_loan_decisions.py hitting an HTTP 502 when fetching external data, which seems unrelated to this PR.\nThe advanced_metricframe doctest passes (50/50), and the added example builds correctly.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/ae1db2500cb89d7e87099c3358902695f1cc1e58", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/009c7d4035a78f056f3649069ad6c091e9fc718f", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/a9ca7822fdc5acc8e253a44ab72d33e77e1de560"], "created_at": "2026-04-12T23:56:58Z"}
{"repo": "fairlearn/fairlearn", "pull_number": 1539, "instance_id": "fairlearn__fairlearn-1539", "issue_numbers": [1537], "base_commit": "27d8a8b998c48e7cc3fb8885e74cf55bce0a1b13", "patch": "diff --git a/examples/plot_adversarial_fine_tuning.py b/examples/plot_adversarial_fine_tuning.py\nindex 11780d5eb..37bef74fe 100644\n--- a/examples/plot_adversarial_fine_tuning.py\n+++ b/examples/plot_adversarial_fine_tuning.py\n@@ -125,12 +125,13 @@ def forward(self, x):\n \n def validate(pipeline, X, y, z, pos_label):\n     predictions = pipeline.predict(X)\n+\n     dp_diff = demographic_parity_difference(\n         y == pos_label,\n         predictions == pos_label,\n         sensitive_features=z,\n     )\n-    accuracy = mean(predictions == y.values)\n+    accuracy = mean(predictions == y)\n     selection_rate = mean(predictions == pos_label)\n     print(\n         \"DP diff: {:.4f}, accuracy: {:.4f}, selection_rate: {:.4f}\".format(\n@@ -219,7 +220,7 @@ def callbacks(model, step, X, y, z, pos_label):\n from fairlearn.metrics import MetricFrame, selection_rate\n \n # to see DP difference, accuracy, and selection_rate\n-print(validate(pipeline, X_test, y_test, z=Z_test, pos_label=pos_label))\n+validate(pipeline, X_test, y_test, z=Z_test, pos_label=pos_label)\n predictions = pipeline.predict(X_test)\n mf = MetricFrame(\n     metrics={\"accuracy\": accuracy_score, \"selection_rate\": selection_rate},\ndiff --git a/fairlearn/adversarial/_adversarial_mitigation.py b/fairlearn/adversarial/_adversarial_mitigation.py\nindex 20b4cf7db..7501d2f07 100644\n--- a/fairlearn/adversarial/_adversarial_mitigation.py\n+++ b/fairlearn/adversarial/_adversarial_mitigation.py\n@@ -514,8 +514,14 @@ def fit(self, X, y, *, sensitive_features=None):\n                 if self.callbacks_:\n                     stop = False\n                     for cb in self.callbacks_:\n+                        y_true = self._y_transform.inverse_transform(y)\n                         result = cb(\n-                            self, step=self.n_iter_, X=X, y=y, z=sensitive_features, pos_label=1\n+                            self,\n+                            step=self.n_iter_,\n+                            X=X,\n+                            y=y_true,\n+                            z=sensitive_features,\n+                            pos_label=self.classes_[1],\n                         )\n                         if result and not isinstance(result, bool):\n                             raise RuntimeError(_CALLBACK_RETURNS_ERROR)\ndiff --git a/fairlearn/adversarial/_preprocessor.py b/fairlearn/adversarial/_preprocessor.py\nindex 68db8c52f..d3f594175 100644\n--- a/fairlearn/adversarial/_preprocessor.py\n+++ b/fairlearn/adversarial/_preprocessor.py\n@@ -11,7 +11,7 @@\n # FIXME: memoize type_of_target. It is quite expensive and called repeatedly.\n \n \n-class FloatTransformer(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):\n+class FloatTransformer(TransformerMixin, BaseEstimator):\n     \"\"\"\n     Transformer that converts input data to numpy arrays of floats.\n \n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "validate() Outputting Zeroes for AdversarialClassifier DP_Diff, Accuracy, and Selection Rate\n<!--\nBefore submitting a bug, please make sure the issue hasn't been already\naddressed by searching through the past issues.\n\nIf your issue is a usage question, please submit it in one of these other\nchannels instead:\n- StackOverflow with the `fairlearn` tag:\n  https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/fairlearn\n- Discord: https://discord.gg/R22yCfgsRn\nThe issue tracker is used only to report bugs and feature requests. For\nquestions, please use either of the above platforms. Most question issues are\nclosed without an answer on this issue tracker. Thanks for your understanding.\n-->\n\n#### Describe the bug\n<!--\n\n-->\nThis function seems to have an issue calculating the DP diff, accuracy, and selection_rate. When using it out-of-the-box, those values are printed as 0.0000 for every step until the last.\n#### Steps/Code to Reproduce\n<!--\nPlease add a minimal example (in the form of code) that reproduces the error.\nBe as succinct as possible, do not depend on external data. In short, we are\ngoing to copy-paste your code and we expect to get the same result as you.\n\nExample:\n\n-->\nRun this file out-of-the-box.\n#### Expected Results\n<!-- -->\nDP_diff, accuracy, and selection_rate should be output every 50 steps to see the model's progress.\n#### Actual Results\n<!-- -->\nDP_diff, accuracy, and selection_rate are printed as 0.0000 every time this function is called. \n#### Versions\n<!--\nPlease provide the following information:\n\n-->\n- OS: Windows\n- Browser (if you're reporting a bug in jupyter): N/A\n- Python version: 3.12.9\n- Fairlearn version: 0.12.0\n- version of:\n    fairlearn: 0.12.0\n       Cython: None\n     lightgbm: None\n   matplotlib: 3.10.0\n        numpy: 2.2.2\n       pandas: 2.2.3\n          pip: 25.0\n      pytorch: None\n        scipy: 1.15.1\n   setuptools: 70.2.0\n      sklearn: None\n   tensorflow: None\n<!-- Thanks for contributing! -->\n\n", "hints_text": "Thanks for the issue @Dylan-Ott! I have some suspicions why this is happening, I will test a few changes this week.\nA very quick exploration led me to this line https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/blob/main/examples/plot_adversarial_fine_tuning.py#L133, where the strings compared do not hold the information in the same format, so the mean is evaluated as 0. I am not sure if the problem is deeper somewhere or it is just formatting issue, leaving this comment for now here if someone that is faster than me to take a look can use a hint. cc @hildeweerts FIY\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Thanks for the issue @Dylan-Ott! I have some suspicions why this is happening, I will test a few changes this week.\nA very quick exploration led me to this line https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/blob/main/examples/plot_adversarial_fine_tuning.py#L133, where the strings compared do not hold the information in the same format, so the mean is evaluated as 0. I am not sure if the problem is deeper somewhere or it is just formatting issue, leaving this comment for now here if someone that is faster than me to take a look can use a hint. cc @hildeweerts FIY\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/c77093a150a359956f7e9b6f07332dca95fd52c1", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/199de1941887861da732c7407d61d61ec775bc88", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/a63bc6e2c41344cd531612a1b3ff259ff79f69e6", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/aab5b3fa8fece84f4f18c87bdd661810163334a8", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/3894fb7acfbd9c1b7ebc63e2e5503435cb4d500c", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/fff256bfccbc03ff35f633a20f99a7e399fec6e7", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/6684e8a79c875a50073fc003cb1d0d055ce52642", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/18d952ce38c5d82f625116092032175f846fa779", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/359d0a2c5824c92cfc5e6596c696b23d22a967e9", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/26913167938ae8d6f953e9f155864e16ebe81819"], "created_at": "2025-04-09T12:51:53Z"}
{"repo": "fairlearn/fairlearn", "pull_number": 1597, "instance_id": "fairlearn__fairlearn-1597", "issue_numbers": [1555], "base_commit": "e3887d785823f8136a8b31688fca286f4cc5c667", "patch": "diff --git a/pyproject.toml b/pyproject.toml\nindex cd290c860..fd019e938 100644\n--- a/pyproject.toml\n+++ b/pyproject.toml\n@@ -40,6 +40,11 @@ filterwarnings = [\n     \"ignore:.*parameter is deprecated and will be removed in Pillow 13.*:DeprecationWarning\"\n ]\n \n+markers = [\n+    \"narwhals: tests that involve dataframe logic backed by Narwhals (deselect with '-m \\\"not narwhals\\\"')\",\n+    \"mpl_image_compare: tests that require 'pytest-mpl' to be installed\"\n+]\n+\n [tool.ruff]\n # Exclude a variety of commonly ignored directories.\n exclude = [\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/test/unit/metrics/test_annotated_metric_function.py b/test/unit/metrics/test_annotated_metric_function.py\nindex 9523a8131..a6dec0fe9 100644\n--- a/test/unit/metrics/test_annotated_metric_function.py\n+++ b/test/unit/metrics/test_annotated_metric_function.py\n@@ -9,6 +9,8 @@\n \n from fairlearn.metrics._annotated_metric_function import AnnotatedMetricFunction\n \n+pytestmark = pytest.mark.narwhals\n+\n \n def test_constructor_unnamed():\n     fc = AnnotatedMetricFunction(func=recall_score, name=None)\ndiff --git a/test/unit/postprocessing/test_plots.py b/test/unit/postprocessing/test_plots.py\nindex eb8543b6f..4782ad73f 100644\n--- a/test/unit/postprocessing/test_plots.py\n+++ b/test/unit/postprocessing/test_plots.py\n@@ -2,8 +2,6 @@\n # Licensed under the MIT License.\n from __future__ import annotations\n \n-from importlib.metadata import PackageNotFoundError\n-\n import pytest\n \n from fairlearn.postprocessing import ThresholdOptimizer, plot_threshold_optimizer\n@@ -48,7 +46,7 @@ def is_mpl_installed():\n         import pytest_mpl  # noqa: F401\n \n         return True\n-    except PackageNotFoundError:\n+    except ModuleNotFoundError:\n         return False\n \n \ndiff --git a/test/unit/preprocessing/linear_dep_remover/test_sklearn_compat.py b/test/unit/preprocessing/linear_dep_remover/test_sklearn_compat.py\nindex 4583c5b1d..c75d4ed9e 100644\n--- a/test/unit/preprocessing/linear_dep_remover/test_sklearn_compat.py\n+++ b/test/unit/preprocessing/linear_dep_remover/test_sklearn_compat.py\n@@ -11,6 +11,8 @@\n \n from fairlearn.preprocessing import CorrelationRemover\n \n+pytestmark = pytest.mark.narwhals\n+\n \n @parametrize_with_checks(\n     [\n", "problem_statement": "TEST Add pytest marker for narwhals\n# Description\n\nThis might look like an odd request, but please bear with me.\nIn Narwhals we take some effort to make sure that what we release/merge does not end up breaking downstream libraries that use Narwhals. We run tests of these libraries as part of our usual CI with Narwhals installing from the PR codebase (see [downstream_tests.yaml](https://github.com/narwhals-dev/narwhals/blob/main/.github/workflows/downstream_tests.yml)).\n\nFor some libraries, these test might take a while and we end up running only specific tests (see [darts example](https://github.com/narwhals-dev/narwhals/blob/63c8e4771a1df4e0bfeea5559c303a4a447d5cc2/.github/workflows/downstream_tests.yml#L534-L536)).\nIn a way this is a hack which might break easily in (at least) the following two scenarios:\n\n- A test is moved -> breaks our CI (happened with plotly)\n- A new test is added and we don't run it -> silent \"failure\"\n\nI would consider Fairlearn to be among the libraries which tests can be quite long in their entirety. \n\n---\n\nIn light of the progressive Narwhals adoption in Fairlearn, I am here to ask what should we test, that also runs in reasonable time.\n\nWould the minimal-deps test suffice? Will there be in the future parts of the code outside of what's tested with minimal-deps workflow that use Narwhals, either directly or indirectly?\n\nOne idea would be to add a `pytestmark = pytest.mark.narwhals` at the top of the test files that run with Narwhals.\nIn this way we simply run `pytest test -m narwhals` to collect all and only these tests, without the need to change it over time.\n\nLet me know if this is a viable idea.\n\n---\n\nNarwhals issue to track it: [narwhals#2603](https://github.com/narwhals-dev/narwhals/issues/2603)\n\n\n", "hints_text": "> I would consider Fairlearn to be among the libraries which tests can be quite long in their entirety.\n\nAgreed  \ud83d\udcaf (I'm working on speeding them up \ud83e\udd1e)\n\n> One idea would be to add a pytestmark\n\nI'm ok with this solution, it would resolve the first breaking case you mentionned (a test is moved), and the second one too (silent failures) provided that we do not forget to mark new narwhals related tests \ud83d\udc4d \n\n@fairlearn/fairlearn-maintainers Any objections ? I guess that in practice this would involve:\n- registring the marker in our [pytest config](https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/blob/main/pyproject.toml#L18).\n- marking some files as @FBruzzesi suggests, (or some specific tests with `@pytest.mark.narwhals` at the top)\nI am also in favour of this, it makes sense for both sides. Maybe we can do a check if a test is added/changed to have a tag like we have for the changelog so we don't forget? \"not a narwhals test\"\n\n", "all_hints_text": "> I would consider Fairlearn to be among the libraries which tests can be quite long in their entirety.\n\nAgreed  \ud83d\udcaf (I'm working on speeding them up \ud83e\udd1e)\n\n> One idea would be to add a pytestmark\n\nI'm ok with this solution, it would resolve the first breaking case you mentionned (a test is moved), and the second one too (silent failures) provided that we do not forget to mark new narwhals related tests \ud83d\udc4d \n\n@fairlearn/fairlearn-maintainers Any objections ? I guess that in practice this would involve:\n- registring the marker in our [pytest config](https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/blob/main/pyproject.toml#L18).\n- marking some files as @FBruzzesi suggests, (or some specific tests with `@pytest.mark.narwhals` at the top)\nI am also in favour of this, it makes sense for both sides. Maybe we can do a check if a test is added/changed to have a tag like we have for the changelog so we don't forget? \"not a narwhals test\"\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/12391b94d0dab65e606e934f6cf1181c897f93ce", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/f0fae5c0370e45dc153cd60ee3d6fd45c2808b81", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/369df6f963540c46f00e4811ec5b15c6d36ba84a"], "created_at": "2025-10-22T12:38:19Z"}
{"repo": "fairlearn/fairlearn", "pull_number": 1596, "instance_id": "fairlearn__fairlearn-1596", "issue_numbers": [1562], "base_commit": "18d88b49212040c0c185dc811a05a257316e2989", "patch": "diff --git a/docs/user_guide/installation_and_version_guide/v0.14.0.rst b/docs/user_guide/installation_and_version_guide/v0.14.0.rst\nindex cc7db5e86..8268c85a9 100644\n--- a/docs/user_guide/installation_and_version_guide/v0.14.0.rst\n+++ b/docs/user_guide/installation_and_version_guide/v0.14.0.rst\n@@ -11,3 +11,4 @@ Other improvements\n ------------------\n \n * Removed support for python 3.9 and added support for python 3.13: :pr:`1592` by :user:`Tamara Atanasoska <tamaraatanasoska>`.\n+* Added support for scipy 1.16 :pr:`1596` by :user:`Tamara Atanasoska <tamaraatanasoska>`.\ndiff --git a/pyproject.toml b/pyproject.toml\nindex fd019e938..9fd4a512a 100644\n--- a/pyproject.toml\n+++ b/pyproject.toml\n@@ -24,7 +24,6 @@ filterwarnings = [\n     \"default:Auto-removal of overlapping axes is deprecated:Warning\",\n     \"default:DataFrame is highly fragmented:Warning\",\n     \"default:The LGBMClassifier or classes from which it inherits use `_get_tags` and `_more_tags`:DeprecationWarning\",\n-    \"ignore:.*The `disp` and `iprint` options of the L-BFGS-B solver are deprecated and will be removed in SciPy 1.18.0.:DeprecationWarning\",\n \n     # Warnings in other-ml (tensorflow)\n     \"default:Type google._upb._message.MessageMapContainer uses PyType_Spec with a metaclass that has custom tp_new:DeprecationWarning\",\ndiff --git a/requirements.txt b/requirements.txt\nindex f82fa5614..2d561826a 100644\n--- a/requirements.txt\n+++ b/requirements.txt\n@@ -2,4 +2,4 @@ narwhals>=1.14.0\n numpy>=1.24.4\n pandas>=2.0.3\n scikit-learn>=1.2.1\n-scipy>=1.9.3, < 1.16.0\n+scipy>=1.9.3\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/test/unit/adversarial/helper.py b/test/unit/adversarial/helper.py\nindex 0fa30daec..f15325ff0 100644\n--- a/test/unit/adversarial/helper.py\n+++ b/test/unit/adversarial/helper.py\n@@ -64,6 +64,11 @@ class fake_torch:\n     def randperm(X):\n         return np.random.choice(range(X), size=X, replace=False)\n \n+    class Tensor:\n+        \"\"\"Mock of torch.Tensor for scipy compatibility.\"\"\"\n+\n+        pass\n+\n     class nn:\n         \"\"\"Mock of torch.nn.\"\"\"\n \ndiff --git a/test_othermlpackages/conda-xgboost.yaml b/test_othermlpackages/conda-xgboost.yaml\nindex 737d1843b..a89369648 100644\n--- a/test_othermlpackages/conda-xgboost.yaml\n+++ b/test_othermlpackages/conda-xgboost.yaml\n@@ -8,7 +8,7 @@ dependencies:\n - pytest-cov\n - xgboost>=1.7.0\n - pandas\n-- scipy<1.16.0\n+- scipy\n \n # Note xgboost not available for Windows on conda-forge\n # See\n", "problem_statement": "MNT Make fairlearn scipy 1.16.0 compatible\n`Scipy` has a new version, 1.16.0. [It introduces some changes] (https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/release/1.16.0-notes.html)that require updating of our codebase.\n\nSome of the issues are [these future deprecations](https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/blob/main/pyproject.toml#L27)(added by @parulgupta1004 to our config, to be removed when a more permanent solution is found), but also other issues. \n\nWhoever takes the issue should remember to remove the limit pointing to version `< 1.16.0` in the `requirements.txt`.\n\n\n", "hints_text": "We will also need to remove the scipy version upper bound on the xgboost config yaml here https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/blob/main/test_othermlpackages%2Fconda-xgboost.yaml#L11\n\n", "all_hints_text": "We will also need to remove the scipy version upper bound on the xgboost config yaml here https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/blob/main/test_othermlpackages%2Fconda-xgboost.yaml#L11\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/ad7ce0fd39fbb15f65259e2687777f7aba67b655", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/76536ebdb62542d2b0a8838739e18af10696dba7", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/b2cb4663aef3b4961dd6d11c89b05609edd2f583", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/c4c1ecf5a89db433282ee1461c8294b31d7db3f4", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/59659660cd368ae0474c42bf8baf8673d9177a0d"], "created_at": "2025-10-21T11:08:15Z"}
{"repo": "fairlearn/fairlearn", "pull_number": 1618, "instance_id": "fairlearn__fairlearn-1618", "issue_numbers": [1586], "base_commit": "e20739376790ca6e0f220044b6b6e47071f78f3b", "patch": "diff --git a/pyproject.toml b/pyproject.toml\nindex 123c788df..1e99bea8b 100644\n--- a/pyproject.toml\n+++ b/pyproject.toml\n@@ -32,9 +32,6 @@ filterwarnings = [\n     # Warnings in test_othermlpackages\n     \"default:The LGBMClassifier or classes from which it inherits use `_get_tags` and `_more_tags`:FutureWarning\",\n \n-    # Warnings in release-wheel\n-    # Pillow\n-    \"ignore:.*parameter is deprecated and will be removed in Pillow 13.*:DeprecationWarning\"\n ]\n \n markers = [\ndiff --git a/requirements-dev.txt b/requirements-dev.txt\nindex 9dd1cb263..76090b587 100644\n--- a/requirements-dev.txt\n+++ b/requirements-dev.txt\n@@ -19,6 +19,7 @@ pytest\n pytest-cov\n pytest-mock\n pytest-mpl\n+matplotlib>=3.10.8\n wheel\n lightgbm\n xlrd\ndiff --git a/requirements-min.txt b/requirements-min.txt\nindex 36576491b..1d57637a1 100644\n--- a/requirements-min.txt\n+++ b/requirements-min.txt\n@@ -12,6 +12,7 @@ pytest==8.3.5\n pytest_cov==6.1.1\n pytest-mock==3.14.0\n pytest-mpl==0.17.0\n+matplotlib==3.10.8\n wheel==0.45.1\n lightgbm==4.6.0\n xlrd==2.0.1\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "MNT Remove a DeprecationWarning (Pillow) in pyproject.toml\nRemove the deprecation suppression and resolve the issue added with #1584.\nThe resolution of this issue would include editing the code to not raise the warning.\n\nThe warning filtered in [pyproject.toml](https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/blob/main/pyproject.toml):\n\n`DeprecationWarning: 'mode' parameter is deprecated and will be removed in Pillow 13 (2026-10-15)`\n\nExample failing test:\n\n`FAILED test/unit/metrics/test_plot_metricframe.py::test_plotting_output - DeprecationWarning: 'mode' parameter is deprecated and will be removed in Pillow 13 (2026-10-15)`\n", "hints_text": "Hello, I would like to work on resolving this issue. If nobody else is already working on it, could you please assign it to me?\n> Hello, I would like to work on resolving this issue. If nobody else is already working on it, could you please assign it to me?\n\nPlease go ahead @iclectic \ud83d\ude4f Don't hesitate to reach out if you need help\n\n\nHi! I\u2019m a first-time contributor and I\u2019d like to work on this issue if it\u2019s still available. Thank you!\nHi @t-nair, please go ahead. It's a bit tricky though because you'll need to investigate the root cause behind the warning. You can see an attempt that was made to fix it here https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/pull/1604 for instance\nHello, I would like to work on resolving this issue. If nobody else is already working on it, could you please assign it to me and i would glad to help you \n\n", "all_hints_text": "Hello, I would like to work on resolving this issue. If nobody else is already working on it, could you please assign it to me?\n> Hello, I would like to work on resolving this issue. If nobody else is already working on it, could you please assign it to me?\n\nPlease go ahead @iclectic \ud83d\ude4f Don't hesitate to reach out if you need help\n\n\nHi! I\u2019m a first-time contributor and I\u2019d like to work on this issue if it\u2019s still available. Thank you!\nHi @t-nair, please go ahead. It's a bit tricky though because you'll need to investigate the root cause behind the warning. You can see an attempt that was made to fix it here https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/pull/1604 for instance\nHello, I would like to work on resolving this issue. If nobody else is already working on it, could you please assign it to me and i would glad to help you \n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/31f08a1df3f1fe90bf9a53a77e539c456d099d2c", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/bd3bd876b8c040b7ea02f52d5e4fa0f2900aacd6"], "created_at": "2026-01-22T14:37:44Z"}
{"repo": "fairlearn/fairlearn", "pull_number": 1592, "instance_id": "fairlearn__fairlearn-1592", "issue_numbers": [1591], "base_commit": "7aade7344af911694198fbaa5579ad64d6f82ada", "patch": "diff --git a/.github/workflows/nightly.yml b/.github/workflows/nightly.yml\nindex f618bf304..9dc92a8fd 100644\n--- a/.github/workflows/nightly.yml\n+++ b/.github/workflows/nightly.yml\n@@ -16,8 +16,8 @@ jobs:\n     uses: ./.github/workflows/test-min-deps.yml\n     with:\n       os: ${{ matrix.os }}\n-      python: \"3.9\"\n-      codeCovPython: \"3.9\"\n+      python: \"3.10\"\n+      codeCovPython: \"3.10\"\n \n   all-deps:\n     strategy:\n@@ -26,12 +26,12 @@ jobs:\n       fail-fast: false\n       matrix:\n         os: [ubuntu-latest, windows-latest, macOS-14]\n-        python: [\"3.9\", \"3.10\", \"3.11\", \"3.12\", \"3.13\"]\n+        python: [\"3.10\", \"3.11\", \"3.12\", \"3.13\", \"3.14\"]\n     uses: ./.github/workflows/test-all-deps.yml\n     with:\n       os: ${{ matrix.os }}\n       python: ${{ matrix.python }}\n-      codeCovPython: \"3.12\"\n+      codeCovPython: \"3.13\"\n \n   minimal-deps:\n     strategy:\n@@ -40,12 +40,12 @@ jobs:\n       fail-fast: false\n       matrix:\n         os: [ubuntu-latest, windows-latest, macOS-14]\n-        python: [\"3.9\", \"3.10\", \"3.11\", \"3.12\", \"3.13\"]\n+        python: [\"3.10\", \"3.11\", \"3.12\", \"3.13\", \"3.14\"]\n     uses: ./.github/workflows/test-minimal-deps.yml\n     with:\n       os: ${{ matrix.os }}\n       python: ${{ matrix.python }}\n-      codeCovPython: \"3.12\"\n+      codeCovPython: \"3.13\"\n \n   other-ml:\n     strategy:\n@@ -57,7 +57,7 @@ jobs:\n     uses: ./.github/workflows/test-other-ml.yml\n     with:\n       os: ubuntu-latest\n-      python: \"3.12\"\n+      python: \"3.13\"\n       mlpackage: ${{ matrix.mlpackage }}\n \n \n@@ -65,7 +65,7 @@ jobs:\n     strategy:\n       matrix:\n         os: [ubuntu-latest]\n-        python: [\"3.12\"]\n+        python: [\"3.13\"]\n     uses: ./.github/workflows/linting.yml\n     with:\n       os: ${{ matrix.os }}\ndiff --git a/.github/workflows/release-wheel.yml b/.github/workflows/release-wheel.yml\nindex e385b0007..a37b2b8ce 100644\n--- a/.github/workflows/release-wheel.yml\n+++ b/.github/workflows/release-wheel.yml\n@@ -42,7 +42,7 @@ jobs:\n     strategy:\n       matrix:\n         os: [ubuntu-latest, windows-latest, macOS-14]\n-        python-version: ['3.9', '3.10', '3.11', '3.12']\n+        python-version: ['3.10', '3.11', '3.12', '3.13']\n     steps:\n     - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n     - name: Set up Python ${{ matrix.python-version }} on ${{ matrix.os }}\ndiff --git a/docs/contributor_guide/development_process.rst b/docs/contributor_guide/development_process.rst\nindex 3e9c69165..8a2ab42eb 100644\n--- a/docs/contributor_guide/development_process.rst\n+++ b/docs/contributor_guide/development_process.rst\n@@ -80,7 +80,7 @@ To verify that the code works as expected run:\n .. note::\n \n    If there is a :code:`torch` related error during the installation,\n-   please downgrade keep your :code:`python` version between 3.9-3.12.\n+   please downgrade keep your :code:`python` version between 3.10-3.13.\n \n Fairlearn currently includes plotting functionality provided by\n :code:`matplotlib`. This is for a niche use case, so it isn't a default requirement. To install run:\ndiff --git a/docs/faq.rst b/docs/faq.rst\nindex 25f9c079f..db589ae71 100644\n--- a/docs/faq.rst\n+++ b/docs/faq.rst\n@@ -172,7 +172,7 @@ Does Fairlearn work for image and text data?\n     data it is operating on).\n \n Is Fairlearn available in languages other than Python?\n-    For the moment, we only support Python >= 3.9\n+    For the moment, we only support Python >= 3.10\n \n Can I contribute to Fairlearn?\n     Absolutely! Please see our :ref:`contributor guide <contributor_guide>` to\ndiff --git a/docs/user_guide/installation_and_version_guide/v0.14.0.rst b/docs/user_guide/installation_and_version_guide/v0.14.0.rst\nindex 0de827387..cc7db5e86 100644\n--- a/docs/user_guide/installation_and_version_guide/v0.14.0.rst\n+++ b/docs/user_guide/installation_and_version_guide/v0.14.0.rst\n@@ -5,3 +5,9 @@ v0.14.0\n \n    v0.14.0 is not yet released. This page reflects changes on the current\n    :code:`main` branch that will eventually be a part of v0.14.0.\n+\n+\n+Other improvements\n+------------------\n+\n+* Removed support for python 3.9 and added support for python 3.13: :pr:`1592` by :user:`Tamara Atanasoska <tamaraatanasoska>`.\ndiff --git a/setup.py b/setup.py\nindex ee158e8ce..3a19bc5de 100644\n--- a/setup.py\n+++ b/setup.py\n@@ -26,13 +26,13 @@\n     long_description_content_type=\"text/markdown\",\n     url=\"https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn\",\n     packages=setuptools.find_packages(),\n-    python_requires=\">=3.9\",\n+    python_requires=\">=3.10\",\n     install_requires=install_requires,\n     classifiers=[\n-        \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.9\",\n         \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.10\",\n         \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.11\",\n         \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.12\",\n+        \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.13\",\n         \"License :: OSI Approved :: MIT License\",\n         \"Operating System :: OS Independent\",\n         \"Development Status :: 3 - Alpha\",\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/.github/workflows/build-test.yml b/.github/workflows/build-test.yml\nindex f18f75c97..c3ff7e175 100644\n--- a/.github/workflows/build-test.yml\n+++ b/.github/workflows/build-test.yml\n@@ -25,37 +25,37 @@ jobs:\n     uses: ./.github/workflows/test-min-deps.yml\n     with:\n       os: ${{ matrix.os }}\n-      python: \"3.9\"\n-      codeCovPython: \"3.9\"\n+      python: \"3.10\"\n+      codeCovPython: \"3.10\"\n \n   all-deps:\n     strategy:\n       matrix:\n         os: [ubuntu-latest, windows-latest, macOS-14]\n-        python: [\"3.9\", \"3.10\", \"3.11\", \"3.12\"]\n+        python: [\"3.10\", \"3.11\", \"3.12\", \"3.13\"]\n     uses: ./.github/workflows/test-all-deps.yml\n     with:\n       os: ${{ matrix.os }}\n       python: ${{ matrix.python }}\n-      codeCovPython: \"3.12\"\n+      codeCovPython: \"3.13\"\n \n   minimal-deps:\n     strategy:\n       matrix:\n         os: [ubuntu-latest, windows-latest, macOS-14]\n-        python: [\"3.9\", \"3.10\", \"3.11\", \"3.12\"]\n+        python: [\"3.10\", \"3.11\", \"3.12\", \"3.13\"]\n     uses: ./.github/workflows/test-minimal-deps.yml\n     with:\n       os: ${{ matrix.os }}\n       python: ${{ matrix.python }}\n-      codeCovPython: \"3.12\"\n+      codeCovPython: \"3.13\"\n \n \n   other-ml:\n     strategy:\n       matrix:\n         os: [ubuntu-latest]\n-        python: [\"3.12\"]\n+        python: [\"3.13\"]\n         mlpackage: [lightgbm, xgboost, tensorflow, pytorch]\n       fail-fast: false\n     uses: ./.github/workflows/test-other-ml.yml\n@@ -69,7 +69,7 @@ jobs:\n     strategy:\n       matrix:\n         os: [ubuntu-latest]\n-        python: [\"3.12\"]\n+        python: [\"3.13\"]\n     uses: ./.github/workflows/linting.yml\n     with:\n       os: ${{ matrix.os }}\ndiff --git a/.github/workflows/test-all-deps.yml b/.github/workflows/test-all-deps.yml\nindex 8dbad3a5b..a0dc2ae07 100644\n--- a/.github/workflows/test-all-deps.yml\n+++ b/.github/workflows/test-all-deps.yml\n@@ -12,7 +12,7 @@ on:\n       codeCovPython:\n         required: true\n         type: string\n-        default: \"3.12\"\n+        default: \"3.13\"\n \n jobs:\n   all-deps:\ndiff --git a/.github/workflows/test-minimal-deps.yml b/.github/workflows/test-minimal-deps.yml\nindex a15c2e860..e8f9b323d 100644\n--- a/.github/workflows/test-minimal-deps.yml\n+++ b/.github/workflows/test-minimal-deps.yml\n@@ -12,7 +12,7 @@ on:\n       codeCovPython:\n         required: true\n         type: string\n-        default: \"3.12\"\n+        default: \"3.13\"\n \n jobs:\n   minimal-deps:\n", "problem_statement": "MNT Discontinue support for Python 3.9, add Python 3.13\nBecause of EOL for Python 3.9 soon, we can remove the support for the version. The nightly has been testing for Python 3.13 for months now and we can safely add it. A nightly testing for the next version should be added too.\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/198827f8a1b8e679eb8b0652340e3153bba765b9", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/c1cbbbcb68b4fbfe85f7e9b6f178999af0ec456d"], "created_at": "2025-10-20T07:56:49Z"}
{"repo": "fairlearn/fairlearn", "pull_number": 1605, "instance_id": "fairlearn__fairlearn-1605", "issue_numbers": [1594], "base_commit": "a200e5f2697d934a6abae195687f3680f27b193e", "patch": "diff --git a/fairlearn/metrics/_fairness_metrics.py b/fairlearn/metrics/_fairness_metrics.py\nindex ec434a5d9..aabffe9eb 100644\n--- a/fairlearn/metrics/_fairness_metrics.py\n+++ b/fairlearn/metrics/_fairness_metrics.py\n@@ -264,7 +264,7 @@ def equal_opportunity_difference(\n \n     The equal opportunity difference is defined as the difference\n     between the largest and the smallest group-level true positive rates,\n-    :math:`E[h(X) | A=a]`, across all values :math:`a` of the sensitive feature(s).\n+    :math:`P[h(X)=1 | A=a, Y=1]`, across all values :math:`a` of the sensitive feature(s).\n     The equal opportunity difference of 0 means that all groups have the same true positive rate.\n \n     Read more in the :ref:`User Guide <disparity_metrics>`.\n@@ -315,7 +315,7 @@ def equal_opportunity_ratio(\n \n     The equal opportunity ratio is defined as the ratio\n     between the smallest and the largest group-level true positive rate,\n-    :math:`E[h(X) | A=a]`, across all values :math:`a` of the sensitive feature(s).\n+    :math:`P[h(X)=1 | A=a, Y=1]`, across all values :math:`a` of the sensitive feature(s).\n     The equal opportunity ratio of 1 means that all groups have the same true positive rate.\n \n     Read more in the :ref:`User Guide <disparity_metrics>`.\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "DOC fix true positive rate formulation in equal opportunity doc\n#### Describe the issue linked to the documentation\nThe [docstring of `equal_opportunity`](https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/blob/main/fairlearn/metrics/_fairness_metrics.py#L267) mistakenly defines the `true_positive_rate` as $`E[h(X) | A=a]`$.\n\n#### Suggest a potential alternative/fix\nTrue positive rate should be defined as $P[h(X)=1 | A=a, Y=1]$\n\n", "hints_text": "I will take this up. ETA Nov 10th\n\n", "all_hints_text": "I will take this up. ETA Nov 10th\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/fd826ee0117b39f1997a432b6694a5635972adb2"], "created_at": "2025-11-27T14:18:37Z"}
{"repo": "fairlearn/fairlearn", "pull_number": 1601, "instance_id": "fairlearn__fairlearn-1601", "issue_numbers": [1595], "base_commit": "d2c42f680ae0e2ed963b1286feb7d89a76f0a557", "patch": "diff --git a/README.rst b/README.rst\nindex 9e58b3c11..26de01474 100644\n--- a/README.rst\n+++ b/README.rst\n@@ -125,7 +125,7 @@ Maintainers\n -----------\n \n A list of current maintainers is\n-`on our website <https://fairlearn.org/main/about/index.html>`__.\n+`on our website <https://fairlearn.org/main/about/index.html#maintainers>`__.\n \n Code of conduct\n ---------------\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "DOC make maintainers hyperlink on README point to Maintainers section on website\n#### Describe the issue linked to the documentation\n\nCurrently, the [hyperlink in the README for the list of maintainers](https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/blob/main/README.rst#maintainers) points to the [About us](https://fairlearn.org/main/about/index.html) page on the website.\n\n#### Suggest a potential alternative/fix\n\nMake the hyperlink point precisely to the [Maintainers section](https://fairlearn.org/main/about/index.html#maintainers) of the About us page.\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "I\u2019ve opened a pull request: [[#1601](https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/pull/1601)]\nJust waiting for review\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/9eb3cece67a4e6c4280809cd42238ab877a03ca2", "https://github.com/fairlearn/fairlearn/commit/8e92f669858d4fca160fa4b6ded490c05c082bd8"], "created_at": "2025-10-25T14:59:52Z"}
